fr:mainmatter.html:div:
while true:

Count occurences of byte pairs. Store in dict D with \{(b_1, b_2): \text {count}\}

Find (b_1, b_2) with highest count.

Merge (b_1, b_2) by (b_{1}, b_{2}) \mapsto  b'

Replace all instances of (b_{1}, b_{2}) in string with b' i.e. 
  b_{1} b_{2} b_{3} b_{4} \mapsto  b'b_{3} b_{4}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Rule 1: d_{\text {ff}} = d_{\text {model}}

d_{\text {model}} is the input dimension

d_{\text {ff}} is the hidden dimension

fr:resource.fr:resource-source:
 \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb, amsmath, stmaryrd, algpseudocodex}
\newenvironment{algo}{\begin{varwidth}{20cm}\begin{algorithmic}}{\end{algorithmic}\end{varwidth}}
\ExplSyntaxOff

\begin {algo}
\State  $m \gets  -\infty ;\quad  d \gets  0$
\For {$i = 1$ \textbf {to} $n$}
  \State  $m_{i+1} \gets  \max (m_i, x_i)$
  \State  $d_{i + 1} \gets  d_i \cdot  e^{\,m_i - m_{i+1}} + e^{\,x_i - m_{i}}$
\EndFor 
\For {$i = 1$ \textbf {to} $n$}
    \State  $\mathbf {p}_{i} \gets  e^{\,x_i - m_n} / d \;$
\EndFor 
\Return  $\mathbf {p}$
\end {algo}

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
We will proceed by directly rewriting the recurrence for \mathbf {o}_{i,k}' as 

  \begin {align*}
    \mathbf {o}_{i,k}' &= \sum _{j = 1}^{k} \frac {\exp (x_{i,j} - m_k)}{d_k} \cdot  \mathbf {v}_j \\
                      &= \left (\sum _{j = 1}^{k - 1} \frac {\exp (x_{i,j} - m_{k-1})}{d_{k-1}} \cdot  \mathbf {v}_j\right ) \frac {d_{k - 1} \cdot  \exp (m_{k-1} - m_{k})}{d_k} +  \frac {\exp (x_{i,k} - m_k)}{d_k} \cdot  \mathbf {v}_k \\
                      &= \mathbf {o}_{i, k-1} \cdot  \frac {d_{k - 1} \cdot  \exp (m_{k-1} - m_{k})}{d_k} +  \frac {\exp (x_{i,k} - m_k)}{d_k} \cdot  \mathbf {v}_k
  .\end {align*}

fr:resource.fr:resource-source:
 \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb, amsmath, stmaryrd, algpseudocodex}
\newenvironment{algo}{\begin{varwidth}{20cm}\begin{algorithmic}}{\end{algorithmic}\end{varwidth}}
\ExplSyntaxOff

\begin {algo}
\For {$i = 1$ \textbf {to} $N$}
\State  $m_{0} \gets  -\infty ;\quad  d_{0} \gets  0$
\For {$j = 1$ \textbf {to} $M$}
  \State  $x_{i,j} \gets  \mathbf {q}_i \cdot  \mathbf {k}_j$
  \State  $m_{j} \gets  \max (m_{j-1}, x_{i,j})$
  \State  $d_{j} \gets  d_{j - 1} \cdot  e^{\,m_{j - 1} - m_{j}} + e^{\,x_{i,j} - m_{j}}$
  \State  $\mathbf {o}_{i, j} \gets  \mathbf {o}_{i, j - 1} \cdot  \frac {d_{j - 1} \cdot  \exp (m_{j-1} - m_{j})}{d_j} +  \frac {\exp (x_{i,j} - m_j)}{d_j} \cdot  \mathbf {v}_j$
\EndFor 
\EndFor 
\end {algo}

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
Following the notation in the original paper, we have the following matrices
\mathbf {S} = \mathbf {Q} \mathbf {K}^T, \quad  \mathbf {P} = \mathrm {softmax}(\mathbf {S}), \quad  \mathbf {O} = \mathbf {P} \mathbf {V}
Now suppose their is some scalar loss function \phi . Then we define 
\frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {O}}, \frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {K}}, \frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {V}}  = d\mathbf {O}, d\mathbf {K}, d\mathbf {V}

html:ol.html:li:
d\mathbf {P}: this is just a straightforward application of the chain rule. In particular, \mathbf {O} = \mathbf {P} \mathbf {V} so that

     d\mathbf {P} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {P}} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {O}} \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}}{\partial  \mathbf {P}} = d\mathbf {O} \mathbf {V}^T



    To sanity check, let us look at the shapes. d\mathbf {O} is the partial with respect to the outputs O, so we need an entry for each output and it is N \times  d. V^T is d \times  N, so that the result d\mathbf {P} is N \times  N as desired.


Furthermore, we can see this by writing \mathbf {O}_{ik} = \sum _{j} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \mathbf {V}_{jk}. Then

      \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {P}_{ij} &= \sum _{i} \frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}} \cdot  \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}}{\partial  \mathbf {P}_{ij}}  \\
                        &= \sum _{i} d\mathbf {O}_{ik} \mathbf {V}_{jk} 
      .\end {align*}

d\mathbf {V}: this is just the same as d\mathbf {P}. In particular, \mathbf {O} = \mathbf {P} \mathbf {V} so that

     d\mathbf {V} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {V}} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {O}} \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}}{\partial  \mathbf {V}} = \mathbf {P}^T d\mathbf {O} 


Furthermore, we can see this by writing \mathbf {O}_{ik} = \sum _{j} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \mathbf {V}_{jk}. Then

      \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {V}_{jk} &= \sum _{i} \frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}} \cdot  \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}}{\partial  \mathbf {V}_{jk}}  \\
                        &= \sum _{i} d\mathbf {O}_{ik} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \\
                        &= \sum _{i} \frac {\exp  \left (\mathbf {Q}_{i} \cdot  \mathbf {K}_{j}\right )}{\mathbf {L}_{i}} d\mathbf {O}_{ik}
      .\end {align*}

d\mathbf {S}: now we apply chain rule with d\mathbf {P}. However, we must take the gradient through the softmax. Exiting matrix notation hell, if we consider the scalar case. Let \mathbf {s} and \mathbf {p} just be rows. Then using the scalar softmax derivation

      \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {s}_j &= \sum _{i} d\mathbf {p}_i \cdot  \frac {\partial  \mathbf {p}_i}{\partial  \mathbf {s}_j} \\  
       &= \sum _{i} d\mathbf {p}_i \cdot  (\delta _{ij}\mathbf {p}_i - \mathbf {p}_{ij}) \\
       &= d \mathbf {p}_{j} \mathbf {p}_{j} - \mathbf {p}_{j}\sum _{i} d\mathbf {p}_{i} \mathbf {p}_{i}
      .\end {align*}

    Now if we rewrite this as the row vector, we get

      \begin {align*}
        d\mathbf {S}_{k} &= \mathbf {P}_{k} \odot  (d\mathbf {P}_{k} - \mathbf {P}_k \cdot  d\mathbf {P}_k)
      .\end {align*}

    To get back to the full matrix, define \mathbf {D}_i = \mathbf {P}_i \cdot  d\mathbf {P}_i i.e. a vector whose ith entry is \mathbf {P}_i \cdot  d\mathbf {P}_i. Then we have that

      \begin {align*}
        d\mathbf {S} &= \mathbf {P} \odot  (d\mathbf {P} - \mathbf {D})
      .\end {align*}

d\mathbf {Q}: To get d\mathbf {Q}, we just apply the chain rule to d\mathbf {S}. Since \mathbf {S} = \mathbf {Q} \mathbf {K}^T,

    \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {Q}_{i} &= \sum _{j} d\mathbf {S}_{ij} \mathbf {K}_{j} \\
                      &= \sum _{j} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \cdot  (d\mathbf {P}_{ij} - \mathbf {D}_i) \mathbf {K}_{j}
    .\end {align*}

d\mathbf {K}: Same as d\mathbf {Q} i.e.

    \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {K}_{j} &= \sum _{j} d\mathbf {S}_{ij} \mathbf {Q}_{i} \\
                      &= \sum _{j} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \cdot  (d\mathbf {P}_{ij} - \mathbf {D}_i) \mathbf {Q}_{i}
    .\end {align*}

